06490nam a22008415i 9780812292695DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162016pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979970132  a97808122926957 a10.9783/97808122926952doi  a(DE-B1597)469613  a(OCoLC)946105808  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aSOC0030002bisacsh04a306.722300aHouses of Ill Repute :bThe Archaeology of Brothels, Houses, and Taverns in the Greek World /ced. by Allison Glazebrook, Barbara Tsakirgis. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b59 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. What Is a House? Conceptualizing the Greek House -- tChapter 2. Can Pottery Help Distinguish a Brothel from a Tavern or House? -- tChapter 3. Patterns of Amphora Discard from Houses, Shops, Taverns, and Brothels -- tChapter 4. Building Z in the Athenian Kerameikos: House, Tavern, Inn, Brothel? -- tChapter 5. Locations of Ill Repute in Late Hellenistic Delos -- tChapter 6. Dining and the Cult of Aphrodite: Th e Function of the South Stoa at Corinth -- tChapter 7. Looking Inside on the Outside of a Pot -- tChapter 8. Is There an Archaeology of Prostitution? -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe study of ancient Greek urbanism has moved from examining the evidence for town planning and the organization of the city-state, or polis, to considerations of "everyday life." That is, it has moved from studying the public (fortifications, marketplaces, council houses, gymnasiums, temples, theaters, fountain houses) to studying the private (the physical remains of Greek houses). But what of those buildings that housed activities neither public nor private—brothels, taverns, and other homes of illicit activity? Can they be distinguished from houses? Were businesses like these run from homes? Classical Athenian writers attest to a diverse urban landscape that included tenement houses (sunoikiai), inns (diaitai, pandokeia), factories (ergasteria), taverns (kapelia), gambling dens (skirapheia), training schools (didaskaleia), and brothels (porneia), yet, despite our knowledge of specific terms, associating them with actual physical remains has not been easy. One such writer, Isaeus, mentions tenement houses that hosted prostitutes and wine sellers, while his contemporary Aeschines refers to doctors, smiths, fullers, carpenters, and pimps renting space. Were tenement houses not simply multi-inhabitant spaces but also multipurpose ones?Houses of Ill Repute is the first book to focus on the difficulties of distinguishing private and semiprivate spaces. While others have studied houses or brothels, this volume looks at both together. The chapters, by leading scholars in the field, address such questions as "What is a house?" and "Did the business of prostitution leave behind a unique archaeological record?" Presenting several approaches to identifying and studying distinctions between domestic residences and houses of ill repute, and drawing on the fields of literature, history, and art history and theory, the volume's contributors provide a way forward for the study of domestic and entertainment spaces in the Hellenic world.Contributors: Bradley A. Ault, Allison Glazebrook, Mark L. Lawall, Kathleen M. Lynch, David Scahill, Amy C. Smith, Monika Trümper, Barbara Tsakirgis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh  aAncient Studies.  aArchaeology.1 aAult, Bradley A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca